<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <%- include('partials/head') %>

  <body>
    <%- include('partials/nav') %>

    <main>
      <section class="food-support-hero">
        <h1>Digital Help in Ladywood</h1>
        <p>
          Understanding digital access challenges in the community and why
          practical support matters.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="food-info">
        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Digital Exclusion in Ladywood</h2>
          <p>
            Digital services are now part of everyday life, from applying for
            jobs and managing benefits to booking appointments, accessing
            healthcare, finding local events and staying connected with others.
            However, not everyone has equal access to the internet, suitable
            devices, or the confidence needed to use online services.
          </p>
          <p>
            Digital exclusion can affect people in different ways. Some
            residents may have limited mobile data, unreliable internet access,
            older devices, or no personal device at all. Others may struggle
            because they lack digital skills, feel unsure about online forms, or
            do not know where to go for help. This can make it harder to access
            support that is increasingly advertised or managed online.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Why Digital Help Matters</h2>
          <p>
            Digital help is important because it can reduce barriers to
            essential services. A resident who cannot confidently use email,
            search online, scan documents, or complete digital forms may find it
            harder to access benefits, housing support, healthcare information,
            employment opportunities or community activities.
          </p>
          <p>
            Support with basic digital tasks can make a significant difference.
            This might include help using a computer, setting up an email
            account, printing or scanning documents, completing online forms,
            using maps, checking opening times, or learning how to stay safe
            online. CommunityLink Ladywood aims to make it easier to find places
            where this type of help may be available.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Access to Devices, Wi-Fi and Printing</h2>
          <p>
            Access to digital infrastructure is not just about having the
            internet. Many online tasks also require a reliable device, a stable
            connection, a printer, a scanner, or someone who can explain the
            process clearly. For residents with limited income, paying for
            mobile data, replacing a device, or travelling to access public
            computers can be difficult.
          </p>
          <p>
            Shared community spaces, libraries, advice centres and digital
            drop-ins can play an important role by providing Wi-Fi, computers,
            printing, scanning and face-to-face support. Clear information about
            where these services are, when they are open, and whether they are
            free can help residents avoid wasted journeys and reduce stress.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Confidence and Digital Skills</h2>
          <p>
            Digital exclusion is not only caused by lack of equipment. Some
            people may have access to a phone or computer but still feel
            uncertain about using websites, online forms, passwords, apps or
            email. This can lead to frustration, anxiety and reliance on others
            for tasks that are increasingly expected to be done online.
          </p>
          <p>
            Digital skills support can help people build confidence gradually.
            Simple, friendly guidance can make online services feel less
            intimidating and help residents become more independent. This is why
            CommunityLink Ladywood focuses on clear categories, simple language
            and practical information rather than overwhelming users with too
            many options.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Accessible Digital Information</h2>
          <p>
            Information about local support must be easy to find and easy to
            understand. A service directory is only useful if it works for
            people with different levels of digital confidence, accessibility
            needs and internet access. Pages should be simple, fast-loading and
            clear on older devices as well as newer ones.
          </p>
          <p>
            CommunityLink Ladywood is designed as a low-data service finder. It
            prioritises text-based information, clear categories, accessibility
            details, opening times and contact information. This helps residents
            and community workers quickly find digital help, Wi-Fi access,
            printing, scanning, advice and other local support in one place.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="food-support-cta">
        <h2>Find Digital Help Near You</h2>
        <p>
          Browse digital help services, Wi-Fi access, printing support and
          community drop-ins available in the Ladywood area.
        </p>
        <a href="/services?category=Digital Help" class="btn-services">
          View Digital Help Services
        </a>
      </section>
    </main>

    <%- include('partials/footer') %>
  </body>
</html>
